{{Infobox character | colour = #DEDEE2 | colour text = | name = Swiebertje | series = | image = Joop Doderer.jpg | caption = | first = 1936 | last = | cause = | creator = [[John Henri uit den Bogaard]] | portrayer = [[Joop Doderer]] | nickname = | alias = | species = | gender = Male | occupation = | title = | family = | spouse = | significantother = | children = | relatives = | religion = | nationality = Dutch }}
'''Swiebertje''' is a character from the books of Dutch author [[John Henri uit den Bogaard]], who wrote a series of children's books based on the character from 1936 to 1974. The books were adapted for television ([[Joop Doderer]] playing the title role), in a series of shows which aired on [[NCRV]] in the 1960s and 1970s, one of the longest-running and most popular shows in Dutch TV history.
==Character and adventures== The character Swiebertje is a tramp, and is supposed to be inspired by a drawing by [[Tjeerd Bottema]]. He is a "lovable vagabond", and his character as well as the TV show "present a comforting image of a simple rural past".<ref>{{cite book|last=Lechner|first=Frank J.|title=The Netherlands: Globalization and National Identity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4geRyL5imswC&pg=PT221|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135907709|page=221}}</ref> His wanderings, during which he typically got in trouble but always found a happy ending, evoked romanticism and adventure.<ref>{{cite book|last=Geelen|first=R.|title=Praktijkboek Dementiezorg|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K0oxLB4Zbz0C&pg=PA302|year=2012|publisher=Bohn Stafleu van Loghum|language=Dutch|isbn=9789031385683|page=302}}</ref> The "innocent" show was the second-most popular show among children in 1966; the most popular was the more adult program ''[[Bonanza]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Noordman|first1=Joannes Maria Antonius|last2=Rietveld-van Wingerden|first2=Marjoke|last3=Bakker|first3=Petronella Catharina Maria|title=Vijf eeuwen opvoeden in Nederland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mT9CrHjhTnUC&pg=PA344|year=2010|publisher=Van Gorcum|language=Dutch|isbn=9789023246138|page=344|chapter=Opvoeding en zorg in 'de eeuw van het kind'}}</ref>
Regular characters included, besides Swiebertje, the police officer Bromsnor ([[Lou Geels]]), housekeeper Saartje ([[Riek Schagen]]), and shopkeeper Malle Pietje ([[Piet Ekel]]).<ref name="oosterwijk">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/prive/article20644801.ece|title='Malle Pietje' haalt herinneringen aan Swiebertje op|last=Oosterwijk|first=Mariët|date=20 July 2008|work=[[De Telegraaf]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref>
==Joop Doderer== On TV, he was played by [[Joop Doderer]], who became so identified with the part that the Dutch expression for the most extreme form of [[Typecasting (acting)|typecasting]], where an actor is identified with just one single character, is called the ''Swiebertje-effect''. [[Oudewater]] has a Swiebertje statue.<ref>{{cite book|title=ANWB Reisgids NL, Utrecht|language=Dutch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qe9PWlbNfxMC&pg=PA97|year=2006|publisher=[[Royal Dutch Touring Club]]|isbn=9789018023102|page=97}}</ref> Doderer played Swiebertje for seventeen years and grew to dislike the character. After the show had run its course, in 1975, he was unable to find serious roles because he was so much identified with Swiebertje; he left for England, where playing roles in high-quality television drama proved a relief. He returned to the Netherlands, and to the stage, and later made peace with the character, saying that Swiebertje derived its popularity from his [[everyman]]-qualities.<ref name="iedereen">{{cite news|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2676/Cultuur/article/detail/667718/2005/09/23/Swiebertje-was-een-man-van-iedereen.dhtml|title=Swiebertje was een man van iedereen|last=Ockhuysen|first=Ronald|date=23 September 2005|work=[[de Volkskrant]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref>
===Adaptations===
The TV series was adapted into a comic strip by Gerrit Stapel. <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/stapel.htm</ref>
